    "id": "undine",
    "nom": "Undine",
    "sousNom": null,
    "race": "Semie",
    "description": "Undines are semi-aquatic beings shaped by ancient oceanic magic, capable of shifting their lower body between a sleek piscine tail and a pair of scaled, amphibious legs. This adaptation allows them to walk on land with surprising agility, though never without discomfort: Undines are biologically and psychologically bound to water. Without regular immersion or at least sustained contact with moisture, they grow anxious, then disoriented, and after a week of complete dryness, their bodies begin to fail.\n\nTheir underwater cities—grown from coral, living stone, and bioluminescent reefs—follow the principle of harmonic flow, a philosophy teaching that decisions must align with emotional and environmental currents. This gives Undines an air of serenity and contemplation, though their communication, rich in subtle gestures and shifts of “emotional currents,” often perplexes surface-dwellers.\n\nWhile generally peaceful, they are not passive: Undines possess long memories and a wary eye toward land cultures. Some live as emissaries or negotiators between sea and shore, but most prefer the safety of their submerged sanctuaries, venturing onto land only with purpose—and always keeping a path back to the water.",
